03698nam a22006735i 9780674262881DE-B159720220524034747.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220524t20222013mau    fo  d z      eng d  a9780674262881  a(DE-B1597)586309  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 4aHD2056.Z8 7aBUS0920002bisacsh1 aCullather, Nick, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Hungry World :bAmerica's Cold War Battle against Poverty in Asia /cNick Cullather. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (368 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aCullather has written an engrossing history of how the United States government, along with private philanthropies like the Ford and Rockefeller foundations, aimed to win the hearts and bodies of rural Asia in the post World War II decades by crafting strategies to develop and modernize agriculture and the peasant’s way of life. He explains how America used foreign aid, modernization theory, nutrition, statistics, and technology, to try to reconstruct the social and political order of the decolonized and disadvantaged countries in the region. Initially the issue of how best to intervene in Asia’s rural countryside was contentious, with clashing visions of development and humanitarian aid being argued throughout the 50’s and 60’s. Ultimately, one strategy displaced all the others—the “Green Revolution” and the ability to feed millions through the miracle of genetically designed dwarf strains of grain and rice. Cullather provides a detailed explanation of how this policy of feeding Asian peasants became the single strategy of “progress” adopted by the US rather than industrialization or land reform. As current controversy swirls about how best to aid Africa in the crisis of nation-building, famine, and a poverty-stricken peasantry, the story of the U.S. interventions in Asia become starkly relevant.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Mai 2022) 0aAgricultural assistance, AmericanzAsia. 0aEconomic assistance, AmericanzAsia. 0aFood reliefzAsia. 0aFood supplyzAsia. 7aBUSINESS & ECONOMICS / Development / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z978311044221240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674262881423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674262881/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999c1893d1999  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA18STMEE  aPDA5EBK